					<div id="background">
						Seeds for All<sup id="fnref:1"><a href="#fn:1" rel="footnote">1</a></sup>	is an international non-governmental association under Swiss Law (Article 60ff. of the Swiss Civil Code.)   Seeds for All was founded by seven international non-governmental organization bound by a common interest in food security, sustainable development, community empowerment and poverty eradication.  The founding members understood that long-term sustainable development and food security will only come about with a debate rooted in the realities of developing countries and including all stakeholders, not just select business and political elite.  The members share the concern that the global conversation on innovation policy and intellectual property rights is not inclusive and in particular discussions regarding plant variety protection does not include or consider the needs and interests of smallholder farmers.[link to background on connection between IP and food security]
						</p><p>
						Indeed, the founders of Seeds for All discovered that the global “mainstream” dialogue on plant variety protection was taking place in Geneva at the UPOV Convention[link to page of website on UPOV], where the only civil society organizations present as observers were from industry.  The founders asked themselves; if the stated mission of UPOV is “to provide and promote an effective system of plant variety protection, with the aim of encouraging the development of new varieties of plants, for the benefit of society”<sup id="fnref:2"><a href="#fn:2" rel="footnote">2</a></sup>surely more input from a broader sector of society is desirable? And so the founding organizations met and established Seeds for All.				</p><p>
							he mission of Seeds for All is to promote plant breeding for the benefit of society, fully implementing farmers’ rights (including those of small and marginal farmers) on plant genetic resources and promoting biodiversity.
						</p>

						
